{"createdTime": 1458749024, "text": "De Pijp, an Amsterdam neighborhood found just south of the canal ring, translates into English as 'The Pipe\u2019 - an early reference to either the public prostitution or the shape of the neighborhood. Historians disagree.  For the last couple of years, an actual pipe, the Amsterdam metro, has been digging its way under De Pijp. Not surprisingly, building a subway in a city that's below sea level is kind of tricky and led to the misfortune which was the 'Great Heineken Debacle of 2014,' when the Heineken brewery fell into a giant sinkhole. Even without its top tourist destination and the constant fear of sudden, gaping pits, De Pijp has managed to evolve into a neighborhood that lifestyle bloggers describe as \u201ctrendy\u201d and \u201calive.\u201d On sunny afternoons, try Sarphatipark if you're inclined to pop the top and get some color. The Albert Cuyp Market (#albertcuypmarkt) is (supposedly) the \u201clargest daytime market in Europe\u201d and has a few interesting food stands, but you're better off heading to Pho 91 (@pho91amsterdam), Spaghetteria (@spaghetteria_pastabar), or The Butcher (@thebutcheramsterdam). (**TIP - There\u2019s also great Surinamese just off the market on Eerste van der Helststraat.) For shopping, there\u2019s Charlie + Mary (@charlieplusmary), All The Luck In The World\u2026 (@alltheluckintheworld), and several other boutiques on the same block of Gerard Doustraat. If you're working away from the office, Stadskantine has plenty of window seating and a good atmosphere. For coffee, Scandinavian Embassy (@scandinavianembassy) and CT Coffee & Coconuts (@coffeecoconuts) are good spots.  Find more suggestions for the best of De Pijp on Sightseen's Neighbourhood Collections.  Download #sightseenapp from the App Store. {"createdTime": 1460471334, "text": "This is Back to Black (@backtoblackcoffee), a great little cafe near the Rijksmuseum.  Whereas in most cities the terms are interchangeable, in Amsterdam, there's definitely a distinction between a \u201ccoffee shop\u201d & a \u201ccafe.\u201d The importance of this distinction depends entirely on your mood, sense of adventure, & probationary status.  All Amsterdamers have stories of visitors naively announcing - \u201cWhere are these weed shops? Let's toke some green!\u201d Nobody sounds cool saying \u201ctoke some green,\u201d & it\u2019s in these situations when Amsterdamers are forced to flip the big kill-switch known as \u201cProject De-escalation: Keep Uncle Steve Away From The Weed.\u201d Step 1 involves a long bike ride followed by trips to brewery/tasting rooms like Borouwer'ij (@brouwerijtij) or Butcher's Tears. If you can sneak in a few rounds of bitterballen with the heavy beers, it\u2019s likely your charge will forget their boastful weed promises.  If Step 1 doesn\u2019t work, Step 2 suggests a visit to a mellow coffee shop & slyly ordering - \u201cMag ik je zwakste weed? I have an idiot tourist who doesn't need anything stronger than hash cut with a ton of rolling tobacco.\u201d Once in hand, take your visitor on a walk to smoke & see the city. They\u2019ll last 30-45 minutes before crashing back at the hotel/AirBnb/your extra bedroom. Easy peasy!  The worst situation is when the visitor stays energetic through the bike ride, dubbels, bitterballen, & your kind offer to order weed. If they say \u201cIt's cool, dude. I\u2019ve smoked a lot of weed, I know the score,\u201d the only option is traditional Dutch directness. \u201cNo, Uncle Steve, you don't know the score. In fact, the score has been hydroponically mutated to such levels that you're going to end up wobbling down Leidsestraat wearing a knit Amsterdam beanie and asking strangers for the \u2018Hanses Blinkers Hotel.\u2019 I don't want to be on a cold bench listening to you repeatedly slur 'I might puke,' while my actual friends have normal evenings. {"createdTime": 1462834469, "text": "\"Geef mij maar Amsterdam, dat is mooier dan Parijs\" - Johnny Jordaan  The Jordaan - traditional home of the dramatic vibrato that is Jordaanlied music and current home of Amsterdam's \u201cmost beautiful canal,\" De Brouwersgracht. A wobbly grid of quiet, narrow streets, the Jordaan is as much Amsterdam heritage as wooden shoes & rain.  On Rozengracht, along the bottom edge of the Jordaan, you'll find Salmuera (@sal_amsterdam) w/ an exceptional mix of cocktails & ceviche. Further down, the terrace at Brandstof (@barbrandstof) is the perfect place to observe one of the great spectacles of Amsterdam \u2013 the convergence of pedestrian, bike, scooter, car, taxi, bus, & tram. Who will win?? (SPOILER \u2013 It's usually the tram.) Heading north off Rozengracht leads into the Jordaan & over some of the city's prettiest canals. If you get nice light & want to win Instagram, Egelantiersgracht (#egelantiersgracht) & Bloemgracht (#bloemgracht) are great options.  Saturday mornings on Westerstraat, you can either have beers & cigarettes with the locals at De Blaffende Vis (#blaffendevis) or head to the organic market at the Noorderkerk (#noorderkerkmarket). If looking for dinner, De Reiger (#dereiger) has maybe the best ribs in Amsterdam & definitely the coolest restaurant cat. Daalder (#daalder), in a former jazz bar on Lindengracht, also has great food, but unconfirmed if there\u2019s a restaurant cat.  After dinner (or anytime really), the Jordaan has a solid supply of brown bars. Cafe Thijsen (@cafe_thijssen) & De Tuin (#cafedetuin) are usually fun. But if you're looking for a truly \u201ccultural\u201d experience, the fluorescent pink, late-night beacon of Cafe Nol (@cafenolamsterdam) will definitely blow up anything you have to do the next morning.  For more Jordaan suggestions, check out the Sightseen app.  Download #sightseenapp from the App Store. {"createdTime": 1466332072, "text": "We love La Stage. It has become one of our favorite intimate restaurants in Amsterdam. Great to impress a date with mouth watering dishes, perfect service and even greater wine and food pairings. This restaurant close to the Nieuwmarkt has applied their proof of a Michelin star in the kitchen and doesn't show it off on their front window. It is exemplary for the modesty of the two partnered owners. In working life they divided the jobs clearly: he is in white, she is in black. {"createdTime": 1467980882, "text": "Our stroll on the Amsterdam Marine Land of the Dutch Navy lead us to the Scheepskameel. Well, to be honest, it was the other way round, because the rumors about this place were very positive. Entering the Scheepskameel you immediately recognize the style of its older sister Rijsel. Both restaurants are housed in historic buildings, the interior tuned to it. This building used to be an education center for Naval chefs. In a new restaurant you would expect a lot of training and learning going on, but the open kitchen seems to be an oasis of tranquillity and harmony. The menu hosts numerous small dishes with a focus on raw ingredients and not too much focus on minimalistic presentations. It is all about the taste and we think it's delicious! In the wine department the Scheepskameel has made the choice to only serve German wines. Daring, but surprisingly well done! The service is of the kind that we would like to see more in Amsterdam. Friendly, courteous, expert.  All in all: this is another go people! {"createdTime": 1468051116, "text": "Our stroll on the Amsterdam Marine Land of the Dutch Navy lead us to the Scheepskameel. Well, to be honest, it was the other way round, because the rumors about this place were very positive. Entering the Scheepskameel you immediately recognize the style of its older sister Rijsel. Both restaurants are housed in historic buildings, the interior tuned to it. This building used to be an education center for Naval chefs. In a new restaurant you would expect a lot of training and learning going on, but the open kitchen seems to be an oasis of tranquillity and harmony. Viscaf\u00e9 De Gouden Hoek, close to the Westerpark, was the first offering mainly Fish and Chips from daily catches. We love the ambiance which is very stylish and strengthening the concept. Here is what they do menu wise: some classic startes like croquettes, oysters and crab, but the main focus is of course on fish and chips. You choose one of the daily catches and combine it with one of three crusts with accompanying sauce. Choose from the classic crust with remoulade, a panko-crust with piccalilli or tempura-crust with Japanese Sriracha. {"createdTime": 1470398349, "text": "We revisited our friends of RIJKS last week because we had something to celebrate. We were almost as satisfied as last time. The food was amazing! Surprising and inspiring dishes that combine the best of food heaven: mouth-watering taste, all different textures creating sensational mouthfeel, cooked to perfection and served in extraordinary ways. This time we sat on the terrace facing the Rijksmuseum in soft yellow raking light. Just like the illumination used by the famous 'Hollandse Meesters' inside. Now partly the weather was at the base of our less experience in service. Also some of the service staff seemed a little out of tone in terms of behavior and clothing. One couldn\u2019t stand still and explained the impressive dishes like he was on some sort of narcotic, while another was afraid to make eye contact and therefore stared at his unpolished shoes. Because RIJKS is still on our Amsterdam Favorites list, we hope they take some time to not only polish the shoes. The kitchen deserves it! We understand \u2014 they\u2019re there, it\u2019s summer in Amsterdam, you\u2019re thinking: \u2018What if we get one of those paddleboats? {"createdTime": 1471003229, "text": "Hoofdstad Brasserie is situated on the waterside of Hotel de L\u2019Europe. It is a beautiful spot overlooking the canals and the Munt Tower. The food is classic and okay, but taking the price into consideration, offers little surprises. Let\u2019s say it is on the safe side. The restaurant has been highlighted by Michelin with a bib gourmand, which stands for 'exceptional good food for moderate prices'. Well, we don\u2019t agree on any of both statements. The hotel was renovated recently but the brasserie still gives you a little bit of an outdated feeling. The terrace furniture is severely affected by the Dutch weather and is ready to be replaced. Service wise: dishes were placed at the wrong guests and service itself isn\u2019t as adequate as you would expect at a 5 star hotel. Come on! {"createdTime": 1487792528, "text": "Half of the Ohmykase team was in Amsterdam this past holiday weekend, and, of course, had to find at least one sushi meal while in the city. We settled on the Michelin-rated Yamazato, located at the Hotel Okura Amsterdam. We were immediately greeted by a friendly waitstaff and seated promptly at the sushi bar. The serenity of the hotel and restaurant itself almost made it feel as though we were transported back to Japan. In particular we liked how the sushi bar was virtually hidden from the main dining room to add a more intimate vibe between those dining at the bar and the two chefs. While we enjoyed the fish quality and the chef's preparation of nigiri, we did think that there was room for improvement with the taste and texture of the rice, as well as with certain ingredients which could use additional refinement to expand the flavors. We do acknowledge that it may be a bit unfair to compare this meal to ones we've had at both Michelin-rated and non Michelin-rated sushi counters in NYC (since the never ending competition in NYC can be a factor in having chefs constantly refine techniques), however,  Yamazato may be worth visiting if you're ever in the mood for a higher-end sushi meal in Amsterdam", "coordinate": {"lat": "52.34858", "lng": "4.89363"}, "locationId": "218128833", "locationName": "Yamazato (Okura)"}
